You can try something like this, bellow
    
    // Register the static hello route
    config.Routes.MapHttpRoute(
         name: &quot;HelloRoute&quot;,
         routeTemplate: &quot;api/hello&quot;,
         defaults: new { controller = &quot;MyTest&quot;, action = &quot;Hello&quot; }
    );
    // If it does not match, then fallback to the generic matcher
    config.Routes.MapHttpRoute(
         name: &quot;DefaultApi&quot;,
         routeTemplate: &quot;api/{controller}/{action}/{id}&quot;,
         defaults: new { id = RouteParameter.Optional }
    );

Take a look at the [microsoft routing guide for web api][1] to see how the matching happens and what default options you have.

Bear in mind that you choose wisely the reason why you want something like this. In case of rest apis we want to have routes like    hostname/resource/id/sub-resource/id

You can read about rest api (which are resource based) [here][2]


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/web-api/overview/web-api-routing-and-actions/routing-in-aspnet-web-api
  [2]: https://github.com/microsoft/api-guidelines/blob/vNext/Guidelines.md

